Exercise 4.5¶

Simulate posterior model:¶

Work with N=100'000 simulations:

In [17]:
N = 100000

Sample N values for $\pi$ from Beta distribution, then sample from binomial distribution with probability $\pi$ and $n=7$ and then restrict to outcomes where shop was still open at 2pm on exactly 3 days:

In [18]:
simulate_posterior <- function( alpha, beta, n, y ) {
    data.frame( pi=rbeta(N, alpha, beta) ) %>% 
        mutate( days_open_at_2pm=rbinom(N, n, pi) ) %>% 
        filter( days_open_at_2pm==y )
}

For Kimya:

In [19]:

Exercise 4.12¶

New prior is not flat anymore but much more concentrated towards large values of $\pi$:

In [45]:
plot_beta( alpha=10, beta=2 )

a)¶

In [46]:
plot_beta_binomial( alpha=10, beta=2, y=10, n=13 )

Few data are available, leading to a moderately different posterior than in 4.11 a).

b)¶

In [47]:
plot_beta_binomial( alpha=10, beta=2, y=0, n=1 )

Only few data are available, leading to a very different posterior than in 4.11 b).

c)¶

In [48]:
plot_beta_binomial( alpha=10, beta=2, y=100, n=130 )

A lot of data is available, leading to almost the same posterior as in 4.11 c).

d)¶

In [49]:
plot_beta_binomial( alpha=10, beta=2, y=20, n=120 )

A lot of data is available, however the prior is highly biased towards high values of $\pi$, still shifting the posterior considerably compared to 4.11 d).

e)¶

In [50]:
plot_beta_binomial( alpha=10, beta=2, y=234, n=468 )

In this case the choice of prior does not matter much because such a big amount of data is available.

Exercise 4.13¶

a)¶

Prior:

In [51]:
pirange <- seq(0, 1, 0.001)
prior <- ifelse(pirange>=0.5, 2, 0)

options(repr.plot.width=10, repr.plot.height=5)
plot(pirange, prior, type="l")

c)¶

Likelihood:

In [52]:
likelihood <- (1-pirange)**100
plot( pirange, likelihood, type="l" )

Posterior:

In [53]:
posterior <- prior*(1-pirange)**100

# make sure that posterior integrates to 1
posterior <- posterior / sum( posterior*0.001 )

plot( pirange, posterior, type="l" )
